commonly impaired","Septic shock cannot occur"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn acute pyelonephritis, \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal function is commonly impaired\u003C/strong\u003E due to inflammation of the renal parenchyma and subsequent tissue damage. While \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood pressure is typically elevated\u003C/strong\u003E, this is not always the case and blood pressure may be low, normal, or high depending on disease severity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGram-positive organisms are not the usual cause,\u003C/strong\u003E as Gram-negative bacteria, particularly \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E, are responsible for approximately 80% of cases. \u003Cstrong\u003EChildren show more specific symptoms than adults\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - children often present with non-specific symptoms like fever, vomiting, and poor feeding, while adults typically report flank pain and dysuria. \u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic shock cannot occur\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as severe pyelonephritis can progress to septic shock, especially in elderly or immunocompromised patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute pyelonephritis is most commonly caused by Gram-negative bacteria, especially Escherichia coli","Acute pyelonephritis can impair renal function and may lead to septic shock in severe cases","Children with pyelonephritis often present with non-specific symptoms compared to adults"],"references":["Belyayeva M, Leslie SW, Jeong JM. Acute Pyelonephritis. 2024 Feb 28. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30137822.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018